<h1>
<a href="http://www.isaac.cs.berkeley.edu/pilot/wingman/">Top Gun
Wingman: WWW Browser for Palm Pilot</a></h1>

<img align="left" src="http://www.isaac.cs.berkeley.edu/pilot/wingman/wmnow.gif">
In addition to scalable Internet proxy service, our other 
prior work concentrates on how to enable
Internet applications for "thin" clients.  Our philosophy is: keep the
client simple, put intelligence in the infrastructure, and design the
infrastructure to be able to support large numbers of clients (hundreds
of thousands or millions).
This philosophy is instantiated in
<a href="http://www.isaac.cs.berkeley.edu/pilot/wingman">Top Gun Wingman</a>,
our high-performance
graphical WWW browser for the Palm Pilot, which is hosted on the same
proxy cluster as <a href="http://transend.cs.berkeley.edu">TranSend.</a>

<br clear="both"><hr>
<h1>
<a href="http://transend.cs.berkeley.edu">TranSend Service Available</a></h1>
<img src="http://transend.cs.berkeley.edu/tlogo_mini.gif" align="left">
<I>TranSend</I> is our scalable WWW proxy, which generalizes and
instantiates the ideas in our earlier <a href="#pythia">Pythia</a>
prototype.  For users with 14.4, 28.8, or Metricom Ricochet modems,
TranSend can speed up Web browsing by a factor of 3 to 7.<p>

The service is open to the public.  We expect to add various
enhancements in the coming months.<p>
<br clear="left">
<P><!---------------------------------------------------------------------->

<H1>Executive Summary</H1>

<P>Our research centers on providing application-level support for computing
models with the following properties: </P>

<UL>
<LI>The client device has modest capabilities compared to a desktop PC
(worse connectivity, less powerful CPU, less memory, small screen) 

<LI>The device is <I>weakly connected </I>to the Internet: primarily intermittent
or low-bandwidth connectivity 
</UL>

<P>Special cases of this general model include mobile computing with PDA's
or laptops, &quot;smart&quot; cellular phones, Network Computers and set-top
boxes, and ISP's serving customers with wireline modems. <BR>
<BR>

The foundation of our approach is <I>proxy-based computing</I>: using
resources on a desktop proxy server to address variation in the network,
client hardware, and client software. Smart proxies allow us to build
lightweight client applications that intelligently adapt to changing
network conditions. <BR> <BR> We work closely with the <A
HREF="http://daedalus.cs.berkeley.edu/">Daedalus/BARWAN project</A>,
which is working on various network-level wireless and mobile computing
projects.
<!--------------------------------------------------------------------------->

