<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="prevwork"></A>Prior Work</h1>

Also see <a
href="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~fox/pubs.html">GloMop-related
publications</a> for refereed papers and documentation on our work.

<DL>
<DT><A NAME="pythia"></A><B><I>Pythia</I> HTTP Proxy</B> </DT>

<DD> Pythia is an early prototype that shows how <A
     HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/glomop/overview.html#distillation">distillation</A>  
     can be exploited for bandwidth management while surfing the Web using a
     slow (e.g. 28.8K) connection. Pythia distills GIF, JPEG, and PostScript,
     and can also strip Java tags and background GIFs and a few other nifty
     things. <br>

     We are no longer running Pythia since it has been replaced by a new
     and much faster service called <i><a
     href="http://transend.cs.berkeley.edu">TranSend</a></i>.  However,
     Pythia is fine for experimenting with this stuff.  Feel free to
     download the <a
     href="ftp://daedalus.cs.berkeley.edu/pub/glomop/pythia.tgz">source
     code</a> and run it at your site.  </DD>

<DT><A NAME="charon"></A><B><I>Charon:</I>
Indirect Kerberos Authentication for Lightweight Clients</B> <BR>
</DT>

<DD>How to provide secure, authenticated proxy services to very lightweight
clients. The protocol, based on Kerberos IV, allows your PDA to securely
connect to a proxy and access proxied services, Kerberized or not. Charon
consists of a proxy side module (portably written in Perl 5, like the rest
of GloMop), and a lightweight client side. We currently have a client implementation
running on the Sony MagicLink PDA. <br>
     Here is the <a
     href="ftp://daedalus.cs.berkeley.edu/pub/glomop/KerberosIV.tgz">
     KerberosIV module for Perl 5.002 or later</a> (unsupported alpha
     code for Perl hackers only).
</DD>

<DT><B><A
     HREF="http://www.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~gribble/magiccap/magiccap.html">
     Proxied MIME Email Reader for Sony MagicLink</A></B> <BR>
</DT>

<DD>An MH-compatible email client that exploits distillation for retrieving
MIME included images. Interestingly, the performance bottleneck is GIF
decoding time on the MagicLink. <BR>
</DD>

<DT><B><A HREF="http://www.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~gribble/cs294-3_multimedia/project/project.html">Real-Time
Streams to PDA's</A></B> <BR>
</DT>

<DD>Why it's hard to do (the CPU is <I>not</I> necessarily the bottleneck!),
and some suggestions for PDA hardware and software makers that will make
it less painful in the future. <BR>
<BR>
</DD>

<DT><B><A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/cs294-3">GloMap: Distillation
on a Geographic Database</A></B> <BR>
<!----------------------------------------------------------------------><BR>
</DT>

<DD>A prototype application for distilling maps. A graphical interface
allows the user to zoom in and out on map data retrieved from a multi-gigabyte
map database stored on an Illustra SQL server. Zooming out decimates the
quality of the outline representation; zooming in (refinement) trades area
for resolution. Unfortunately the demo can no longer be run, because I
no longer have access to the SQL data. But if you are interested in seeing
this and want to pursue it as a long-term project, I can try to get access
again.
</DD>
</DL>

