<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Work In Progress</H1>
d160 3
a162 47
<DL>
<DT><B>Wink Internet</B></DT>
<B></B>
<DD>We have been working with <A HREF="http://www.wink.com">Wink Communications</A>
to extend the reach of the Internet seamlessly to Wink-empowered devices.
The <A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/glomop/index.html#glomop_proxy">core
GloMop software</A> was used as the foundation for building the solution.
We are continuing to discuss lightweight client support layers. </DD>

<DT><B>Berkeley DCNS&nbsp;World Wide Web Proxy</B></DT>
<B></B>
<DD>Based on experience with our <A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/glomop/index.html#anchor205778">Pythia
</A>prototype, we are developing a distillation-based WWW&nbsp;proxy with
which we hope to serve a substantial fraction of Berkeley's Dialup IP&nbsp;users,
served by the Data Communications and Network Services office. A large
number of these users access the WWW via 14 .4 or 28.8 modems, and more
recently a few have also begun using <A HREF="http://www.metricom.com">Metricom</A>
wireless modems; we hope to increase the performance of their Web surfing
experience while leveraging all of the computational ability of their Netscape
clients. The multithreaded design will leverage the Berkeley <A HREF="http://now.cs.berkeley.edu">NOW</A>,
<A HREF="http://now.cs.berkeley.edu/active_messages.html">Active Messages</A>,
and the Colorado/USC <A HREF="http://harvest.cs.colorado.edu">Harvest </A>Cache
as well as our own experience with <A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/glomop/index.html#glomop_proxy">on-demand
dynamic distillation</A>.</DD>

<DT><B>Pilot WWW&nbsp;Browser based on GloMopLite</B></DT>
<B></B>
<DD>To see how well our philosophy of &quot;keep the client simple&quot;
really works, and to test the limits of GloMop's ability to adapt content
for severely restricted clients, we are writing a WWW&nbsp;browser and
GloMop Lite stack for the <A HREF="http://www.usr.com/palm/">USR&nbsp;Pilot</A>.
Because we do not rely on the heavyweight TCP stack, and because the GloMop
protocol is heavily optimized for delivery of typed content over slow links,
we expect that the performance of this software will compare more than
favorably with the performance of commercially available text-only WWW
browsers. </DD>

<UL>
<LI>We expect to make the Pilot software freely available when it is ready;
watch this space for details. </LI>
</UL>
</DL>

<P>
<HR width="100%"></P>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><A NAME="anchor740019"></A>Recent Work &amp;&nbsp;Publications</H1>
d165 1
a165 24
<DT><A NAME="glomop_proxy"></A><B>The GloMop Proxy Architecture</B> </DT>

<DD><BR>
GloMop is the core of our proxy architecture for exploring on-demand dynamic
distillation. GloMop is a modular proxy written in Perl 5 and C. As of
this writing, it supports connection via TCP sockets or serial (raw or
modem), authentication using <A HREF="http://HTTP.CS.Berkeley.EDU/~fox/glomop/abstracts.html#charon">Charon</A>,
secure remote login, and distillation and refinement modules for HTML&nbsp;WWW
pages and images. GloMop is our platform for investigating application
partitioning strategies for lightweight clients, agent-based computing,
and extensible modular application proxies, and is the reference point
for our &quot;vision&quot; of proxy-based computing. </DD>

<UL>
<LI><I>Adapting to Network and Client Variation via On-Demand Dynamic Transcoding.
<BR>
